Machine learning prediction of cattle supply sheds

2024-03-23

Machine learning prediction of cattle supply sheds - i.e.the proportion of cattle sourced per municipality.

Load data

# Logistic hub data
lh <- 
  s3read_using(
    object = "brazil/logistics/slaughterhouses/slaughterhouse_map_v3/2022-06-09-br_beef_logistics_map_v3.csv",
    delim = ";",
    FUN = read_delim,
    col_types = cols(CNPJ = col_character(),
                     GEOCODE = col_character(),
                     INSPECTION_NUM = col_character()),
    opts = c("check_region" = T),
    bucket = ts
  )


# Clean columns
lh <- lh %>%
  mutate(CNPJ8 = str_sub(CNPJ, start = 1, end = 8)) %>%
  mutate(REGION = case_when(
      STATE %in% c("DF", "GO", "MT", "MS") ~ "Centro-Oeste",
      STATE %in% c("AL", "BA" , "CE", "MA", "PB", "PE", "PI", "RN", "SE") ~ "Nordeste",
      STATE %in% c("AC", "AP", "AM", "PA", "RO", "RR", "TO") ~ "Norte",
      STATE %in% c("ES", "MG", "RJ", "SP") ~ "Sudeste",
      STATE %in% c("PR", "SC", "RS") ~ "Sul",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
      ), 
      REGION = str_to_upper(REGION)) %>%
  rename(LH_GEOCODE = GEOCODE)


# Supply sheds
ss <- s3read_using(
  object = "brazil/logistics/gta/network/BOV/SUPPLY_SHED/2024_MUNICIPAL_PER_CNPJ8/JSON/CNPJ8_SUPPLY_SHEDS.json", 
  FUN = fromJSON, 
  bucket = ts
)


# Drop supply sheds, that on second thoughts I think look unreliable

ppm_2022 <- ppm %>% filter(YEAR == 2022) %>% select(-YEAR)


# Load SIGSIF data on the origin of cattle slaughtered in each state
# ... keep only relevant columns, drop unknown GEOCODEs
# ... ensure that the sum of the proportions (PROP_FLOWS) per state sums to 1.
sigsif_summary <- 
  s3read_using(
    object = "brazil/production/statistics/sigsif/out/old/br_bovine_slaughter_2015_2020.csv", 
    FUN = read_delim,
    col_types = cols(GEOCODE = col_character()),
    delim = ";",
    bucket = ts,
    opts = c("check_region" = T)
  )
sigsif_summary <- sigsif_summary %>%
  filter(GEOCODE != "XXXXXXX") %>%
  group_by(STATE_SLAUGHTER) %>%
  mutate(TOTAL_PROP_FLOWS = sum(PROP_FLOWS)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(SIGSIF_PROP_FLOWS = PROP_FLOWS / TOTAL_PROP_FLOWS) %>%
  select(STATE_SLAUGHTER, 
         GEOCODE, 
         SIGSIF_PROP_FLOWS)

if(fs::file_exists(here::here("tmp/DISTANCE_MATRIX_2016.csv"))){

# Load municipal borders 
munis <-
  s3read_using(
    object = "brazil/spatial/BOUNDARIES/ibge/old/boundaries municipalities/MUNICIPALITIES_BRA.geojson",
    FUN = read_sf,
    bucket = "trase-storage",
    opts = c("check_region" = T)
  )
muni_centroids <- st_centroid(munis)


# Load state borders shp
path <- "brazil/spatial/BOUNDARIES/ibge/old/boundaries states/"
keys <- map_chr(get_bucket(ts, prefix = path), "Key")
walk(keys, ~ save_object(., ts, file = str_c(tempdir(),"/", basename(.))))
objects <- list.files(tempdir(), pattern = "BRUFE250GC_SIR", full.names = TRUE)
objects_main <- objects[grepl("\\.shp", objects)]
states <- read_sf(objects_main)
rm(path, keys, objects, objects_main)
states <- states %>%
  mutate(NM_ESTADO = str_trans(NM_ESTADO))


# Identify directly neighbouring municipalities
# ... Inspired by https://github.com/r-spatial/sf/issues/234
neighbour_mtx <- st_intersects(munis, munis)
neighbour_df <- as.data.frame(neighbour_mtx) %>%
  janitor::clean_names("screaming_snake")
munis_df <- munis %>% 
  st_drop_geometry() %>% 
  mutate(ROW_ID = row_number()) %>%
  select(ROW_ID, GEOCODE) 
neighbour_df <-   
  neighbour_df %>% 
  left_join(munis_df, by = "ROW_ID") %>%
  rename(FOCAL_GEOCODE = GEOCODE) %>%
  left_join(munis_df, by = c("COL_ID" = "ROW_ID")) %>%
  rename(NEIGHBOUR_GEOCODE = GEOCODE) %>%
  mutate(NEIGHBOUR = ifelse(FOCAL_GEOCODE == NEIGHBOUR_GEOCODE, "SAME", "NEXT-DOOR")) %>%
  select(FOCAL_GEOCODE, NEIGHBOUR_GEOCODE, NEIGHBOUR) %>%
  as_tibble()
stopifnot(any(is.na(neighbour_df$NEIGHBOUR_GEOCODE)) == FALSE)
stopifnot(any(is.na(neighbour_df$FOCAL_GEOCODE)) == FALSE)


# Identify neighbouring municipalities, one step removed
# ... i.e. Neighbours of neighbours
next_neighbours_df <- left_join(neighbour_df, neighbour_df, by = c("NEIGHBOUR_GEOCODE" = "FOCAL_GEOCODE"), suffix = c("_ORIGINAL", "_NEXTDOOR"), relationship = "many-to-many") %>%
  filter(FOCAL_GEOCODE != NEIGHBOUR_GEOCODE, 
         NEIGHBOUR_GEOCODE != NEIGHBOUR_GEOCODE_NEXTDOOR, 
         FOCAL_GEOCODE != NEIGHBOUR_GEOCODE_NEXTDOOR) %>%
  distinct(FOCAL_GEOCODE, NEIGHBOUR_GEOCODE_NEXTDOOR) %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  mutate(NEIGHBOUR = "ONCE-REMOVED") %>%
  rename(NEIGHBOUR_GEOCODE = NEIGHBOUR_GEOCODE_NEXTDOOR)


# Remove duplicates (municipalities which are both direct neighbours and also once-removed neighbours
next_neighbours_df <- left_join(next_neighbours_df, neighbour_df, by = c("FOCAL_GEOCODE", "NEIGHBOUR_GEOCODE")) %>%
  mutate(NEIGHBOUR = coalesce(NEIGHBOUR.y, NEIGHBOUR.x)) %>%
  select(FOCAL_GEOCODE, NEIGHBOUR_GEOCODE, NEIGHBOUR) 


# Join the immediate and next-door neighbours df
neighbour_all_df <- bind_rows(neighbour_df, next_neighbours_df) %>% 
  distinct()


# Check no GEOCODE pairs with multiple classifications (same, neighbour, neighbour-one-removed)
stopifnot(
  neighbour_all_df %>% group_by(FOCAL_GEOCODE, NEIGHBOUR_GEOCODE) %>% count() %>% filter(n > 1) %>% nrow() == 0
  )


# Visualise an example to check it looks OK
focal_muni <- neighbour_all_df %>% sample_n(size = 1) %>% pull(FOCAL_GEOCODE)
munis_to_plot <- inner_join(munis, neighbour_all_df %>% filter(FOCAL_GEOCODE == focal_muni), by = c("GEOCODE" = "NEIGHBOUR_GEOCODE"))

# Identify the distance to the nearest SIF and SIE slaughterhouse per municipality
# ... Note I keep just the two closest distances in each case
# ... when joining these data to the data-frame, this allows us to find the nearest slaughterhouse
# ... which is NOT the slaughtehrouse-of-interest (hence the need for two results here)
sifs <- lh %>%
  filter(INSPECTION_LEVEL == "SIF") %>%
  distinct(CNPJ8, LH_GEOCODE)
sif_distances <- inner_join(dist_matrix, sifs, by = c("DESTINATION" = "LH_GEOCODE"), relationship = "many-to-many") %>%
  group_by(ORIGIN) %>%
  arrange(DISTANCE_KM) %>%
  slice(1:2) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(ORIGIN, 
         DISTANCE_KM_TO_NEXT_NEAREST_SIF = DISTANCE_KM, 
         CNPJ8_SIF = CNPJ8)
sies <- lh %>%
  filter(INSPECTION_LEVEL == "SIE") %>%
  distinct(CNPJ8, LH_GEOCODE)
sie_distances <- inner_join(dist_matrix, sies, by = c("DESTINATION" = "LH_GEOCODE"), relationship = "many-to-many") %>%
  group_by(ORIGIN) %>%
  arrange(DISTANCE_KM) %>%
  slice(1:2) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(ORIGIN, 
         DISTANCE_KM_TO_NEXT_NEAREST_SIE = DISTANCE_KM, 
         CNPJ8_SIE = CNPJ8)
rm(sifs, sies)

This is what we want to predict:

fn_plot_cnpj8_supply_sheds <- function(CNPJ8, LH_GEOCODE, SUPPLY_SHED, TOTAL_NUM_DIRECT_GTAS, TOTAL_NUM_GTAS, muni_centroids, states, scale_max) {
  munis_to_plot <-
    inner_join(munis, SUPPLY_SHED, by = c("GEOCODE" = "GEOCODE")) %>%
    mutate(TWO_DIGIT_CODE = str_sub(GEOCODE, start = 1, end = 2)) %>%
    left_join(state_dic, by = "TWO_DIGIT_CODE")
  location <-
    muni_centroids %>%
    filter(GEOCODE == LH_GEOCODE) %>%
    mutate(
      x = map_dbl(geometry, 1),
      y = map_dbl(geometry, 2), 
      TWO_DIGIT_CODE = str_sub(GEOCODE, start = 1, end = 2)
    ) %>%
    left_join(state_dic, by = "TWO_DIGIT_CODE")
  p <- ggplot() +
    geom_sf(data = states %>% filter(NM_ESTADO %in% unique(munis_to_plot$STATE_NAME)), fill = trase_country_background, col = trase_map_border) +
    geom_sf(data = munis_to_plot, aes(fill = PROP_FLOWS * 100), col = NA) +
    geom_point(data = location, aes(x = x, y = y), col = "green") +
    scale_fill_gradient(
    name = bquote('% SOURCING'),
    low = trase_palettes$MapsNegative[[1]],
    high = trase_palettes$MapsNegative[[9]], 
    limits = c(0, 100)
  ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    coord_sf(datum = NA) +
    labs(
      title = paste0("Sourcing of CNPJ8 ", CNPJ8, " in ", location$NAME, ", ", location$STATE_ABBR),
      subtitle = paste0("Based on ", TOTAL_NUM_DIRECT_GTAS, " direct GTAs & network of ", TOTAL_NUM_GTAS, " GTAs")
    ) +
    theme(axis.title = element_blank())
  return(p)
}
pmap(
  .l = ss %>% sample_n(size = 4),
  .f = fn_plot_cnpj8_supply_sheds,
  muni_centroids = muni_centroids,
  states = states,
  scale_max = max(supply_sheds_cnpj8$PROP_FLOWS) + 2
)

ss_all <- ss %>% 
  unnest(cols = c(SUPPLY_SHED)) %>% 
  filter(!grepl("AGGREGATED", GEOCODE)) %>%
  select(-BIOME) %>% 
  complete(
    GEOCODE,
    nesting(CNPJ8, LH_GEOCODE, TOTAL_NUM_DIRECT_GTAS, TOTAL_NUM_GTAS),
    fill = list(PROP_FLOWS = 0)
    ) 


# Check the complete() worked, and all municipalities are included in the supply shed of each slaughterhouse

The data.frame used to construct the model is:

# Make a single dataframe with all the relevant data
df <- lh %>%
  select(CNPJ8, LH_GEOCODE, REGION, STATE, TYPE, INSPECTION_LEVEL) %>%
  left_join(ss_all, by = c("CNPJ8", "LH_GEOCODE"), relationship = "many-to-many") %>%
  select(-TOTAL_NUM_DIRECT_GTAS, -TOTAL_NUM_GTAS) %>%
  left_join(ppm_2022, by = "GEOCODE", relationship = "many-to-one") %>%
  left_join(urban, by = c("LH_GEOCODE" = "GEOCODE"), relationship = "many-to-one") %>%
  rename(LH_CLASSIFICATION = MUNI_CLASSIFICATION) %>%
  left_join(urban, by = c("GEOCODE" = "GEOCODE"), relationship = "many-to-one") %>%
  rename(GEOCODE_CLASSIFICATION = MUNI_CLASSIFICATION) %>%
  left_join(sigsif_summary, by = c("STATE" = "STATE_SLAUGHTER", "GEOCODE")) %>%
  mutate(PROP_FLOWS = replace_na(PROP_FLOWS, 0), 
         NUM_HEAD = replace_na(NUM_HEAD, 0), 
         SIGSIF_PROP_FLOWS = replace_na(SIGSIF_PROP_FLOWS, 0)) %>%
  left_join(dist_matrix, by = c("LH_GEOCODE" = "DESTINATION", "GEOCODE" = "ORIGIN")) %>%
  left_join(neighbour_all_df, by = c("LH_GEOCODE" = "FOCAL_GEOCODE", "GEOCODE" = "NEIGHBOUR_GEOCODE")) %>%
  mutate(NEIGHBOUR = ifelse(is.na(NEIGHBOUR), "NOT NEIGHBOUR", NEIGHBOUR)) %>%
  mutate(SAME_STATE = ifelse(str_sub(LH_GEOCODE, start = 1, end = 2) == str_sub(GEOCODE, start = 1, end = 2), TRUE, FALSE)) %>%
  distinct()


# Add in missing data - these are cases where our transport matrix is missing municipality-pairs.
# ... I took the numbers from: https://www.freemaptools.com/how-far-is-it-between.htm
df <- df %>%
  mutate(
    DISTANCE_KM = case_when(
      LH_GEOCODE == "1502400" & GEOCODE == "1504901" ~ 146.923,
      LH_GEOCODE == "1502301" & GEOCODE == "1504901" ~ 241.071,
      LH_GEOCODE == "1501709" & GEOCODE == "1504901" ~ 278.366,
      LH_GEOCODE == "1501303" & GEOCODE == "1504901" ~ 67.096,
      LH_GEOCODE == "4307906" & GEOCODE == "4314548" ~ 25.709,
      LH_GEOCODE == "2610707" & GEOCODE == "2616183" ~ 136.084,
      LH_GEOCODE == "2616407" & GEOCODE == "2616183" ~ 97.839,
      LH_GEOCODE == "4316758" & GEOCODE == "4314548" ~ 105.442,
      TRUE ~ DISTANCE_KM
    )
  )


# Drop rows with NAs, these are because of gaps in the various datasets
df <- df %>%
  drop_na(GEOCODE) %>%
  drop_na(DISTANCE_KM) %>%
  drop_na(LH_CLASSIFICATION) %>%
  drop_na(GEOCODE_CLASSIFICATION)


# Add in the distance to the nearest SIF/SIE slaughterhouse (which is no the slaughterhouse-of-interest)

                 sif_distances,

Fit random forest model

training_size <- 0.9

Fit the model to 90% of the data (the training data).

# Split the data
df <- df %>%
  group_by(CNPJ8, LH_GEOCODE) %>%
  nest() %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(ROWNUM = row_number())
training <- df %>%
  sample_n(size = round(nrow(df) * training_size)) %>%
  unnest(cols = c(data))
test <- df %>%
  filter(!ROWNUM %in% training$ROWNUM) %>%
  unnest(cols = c(data))
df <- df %>% unnest(cols = c(data))
# Fit the model
ml <- ranger(data = training, PROP_FLOWS ~ REGION + TYPE + INSPECTION_LEVEL + NUM_HEAD + SIGSIF_PROP_FLOWS + DISTANCE_KM + NEIGHBOUR + SAME_STATE + LH_CLASSIFICATION + GEOCODE_CLASSIFICATION + DISTANCE_KM_TO_NEXT_NEAREST_SIF + DISTANCE_KM_TO_NEXT_NEAREST_SIE, 
             importance = 'permutation')

Next, we rebase the proportions to 1, and visualise the in-sample correlation between observed and predicted:

# Compare the actual and predicted PROP_FLOWS
# ... Note, since the predicted PRED_PROP_FLOWS don't necessarily sum to one (for each slaughterhouse)
# ... I include a correction, were we re-base the PROP_FLOWS to sum to 1 (i.e. a true-proportion)
df2 %>%
  group_by(CNPJ8, LH_GEOCODE) %>%
  mutate(TOTAL_PRED_PROP_FLOWS = sum(PRED_PROP_FLOWS)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(PRED_PROP_FLOWS_CORRECTED = PRED_PROP_FLOWS / TOTAL_PRED_PROP_FLOWS) %>%
  ggplot(aes(PROP_FLOWS, PRED_PROP_FLOWS_CORRECTED)) + 
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~STATE) +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1)) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 1))

Compute the RF 20 times and collect statistics.

ra_stats <- data.frame(rep=1:n, rsq=as.numeric(NA), mse=as.numeric(NA))
ra_importance <- vector(mode = "list", length = n)
for (i in 1:n) {
  model.ra <- ranger(data = training, PROP_FLOWS ~ REGION + TYPE + INSPECTION_LEVEL + NUM_HEAD + SIGSIF_PROP_FLOWS + DISTANCE_KM + NEIGHBOUR + SAME_STATE + LH_CLASSIFICATION + GEOCODE_CLASSIFICATION, 
             importance = "permutation", 
             write.forest = FALSE)
  ra_stats[i, "mse"] <- model.ra$prediction.error
  ra_stats[i, "rsq"] <- model.ra$r.squared
  model_importance <- importance(model.ra)
  ra_importance[[i]] <- 
  tibble("VARIABLE" = names(model_importance), 
         "VALUE" = model_importance)
  rm(model_importance, model.ra)
}

Deforestation risk correlation

Does the deforestation risk correlate better than the raw supply shed (proportion sourced per municipality)?

# Load pasture & cattle deforestation data, and production data
cd <- s3read_using(
  object = "data/DEFORESTATION/2024-02-15-br_mun_biome_pasture_cattle_deforestation_2013_2022_q4_2023_gee.csv",
  FUN = read_delim,
  delim = ",",
  bucket = "trase-app",
  opts = c("check_region" = T)
) %>% 
  select(where(~!all(is.na(.x))))


# Past pasture deforestation
# ... Because we now use the full life cycle deforestation, we divide by five to get the mean per year ha/ton
# ... (in the previous version of the data we used the ANNUAL)
# ... this avoids double-counting across years, as 2018 pasture deforestation is calculated with deforestation in 2014-2018
ppd <- 
  cd %>%
  mutate(GEOCODE = gsub("BR-", "", TRASE_ID)) %>%
  select(GEOCODE, PASDEFOR_2022, PASDEFOR_2021, PASDEFOR_2020, PASDEFOR_2019, PASDEFOR_2018) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(PASDEFOR_2022, PASDEFOR_2021, PASDEFOR_2020, PASDEFOR_2019, PASDEFOR_2018),
               names_to = "YEAR", 
               values_to = "VALUE") %>%
  group_by(GEOCODE) %>%
  summarise(PASTURE_DEFORESTATION = sum(VALUE) / 5) %>%
  ungroup()


# Past cattle deforestation 
# ... Because we now use the full life cycle deforestation, we divide by five to get the mean per year ha/ton
# ... (in the previous version of the data we used the ANNUAL)
# ... this avoids double-counting across years
pcd <- 
  cd %>%
  mutate(GEOCODE = gsub("BR-", "", TRASE_ID)) %>%
  select(GEOCODE, CATTLE_DEFOR_MUNBIO_FULL_2022, CATTLE_DEFOR_MUNBIO_FULL_2021, CATTLE_DEFOR_MUNBIO_FULL_2020, CATTLE_DEFOR_MUNBIO_FULL_2019,CATTLE_DEFOR_MUNBIO_FULL_2018) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(CATTLE_DEFOR_MUNBIO_FULL_2022, CATTLE_DEFOR_MUNBIO_FULL_2021, CATTLE_DEFOR_MUNBIO_FULL_2020, CATTLE_DEFOR_MUNBIO_FULL_2019,CATTLE_DEFOR_MUNBIO_FULL_2018),
               names_to = "YEAR", 
               values_to = "VALUE") %>%
  group_by(GEOCODE) %>%
  summarise(CATTLE_DEFORESTATION_FULL = sum(VALUE) / 5) %>%
  ungroup()


# Merge into a single df
ppd <- full_join(ppd, pcd, by = "GEOCODE") %>%
  mutate(CATTLE_DEFORESTATION_FULL = replace_na(CATTLE_DEFORESTATION_FULL, 0), 
         PASTURE_DEFORESTATION = replace_na(PASTURE_DEFORESTATION, 0))
# Add deforestation data to the supply sheds
# NB I use the cattle deforestation per THOUSAND tons of carcass
df_deforestation <- df2 %>%
  group_by(CNPJ8, LH_GEOCODE) %>%
  mutate(TOTAL_PRED_PROP_FLOWS = sum(PRED_PROP_FLOWS)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(PRED_PROP_FLOWS_CORRECTED = PRED_PROP_FLOWS / TOTAL_PRED_PROP_FLOWS) %>%
  left_join(ppd, ., by = "GEOCODE") %>%
  mutate(WEIGHTED_CATTLE_DEF = PROP_FLOWS * CATTLE_DEFORESTATION_FULL * 1000, 
         WEIGHTED_CATTLE_DEF_PRED = PRED_PROP_FLOWS_CORRECTED * CATTLE_DEFORESTATION_FULL * 1000) %>%
  group_by(CNPJ8, LH_GEOCODE) %>%
  summarise(SUM_CD_ORIGINAL = sum(WEIGHTED_CATTLE_DEF, na.rm = T),
            SUM_CD_PRED = sum(WEIGHTED_CATTLE_DEF_PRED, na.rm = T)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(DFRS_SOURCE = "GTA")


# Check the deforestation correlation
df_model <- lm(data = df_deforestation, SUM_CD_ORIGINAL ~ SUM_CD_PRED)

Th r-sq of the deforestation model is: 0.8884133.

Predict supply sheds

For the slaughterhouses where we do not have GTAs, predict the supply shed.

# Build the dataset for prediction
# ... this requires adding a row per municipality in the country, per slaughterhouse
# ... and also filtering to ABATEDOURO/MATADOUROs
# ... for the rest (ENTREPOSTO FRIGORIFICO, UNIDADE DE BENEFICIAMENTO), they don't usually buy cattle directly
# ...a also I drop cases where the municipality-pairs have no transport data
# ... this is mostly cases to MUAN, PA or PEDRA BRANCA DO AMAPARI, AP where there
# ... are few cattle and the travel algorithm failed to find solutions, due to crossing 
# ... the Amazon, I suppose
lh_missing <- lh %>%
  anti_join(ss, by = c("CNPJ8", "LH_GEOCODE")) %>%
  select(CNPJ8, LH_GEOCODE, REGION, STATE, TYPE, INSPECTION_LEVEL) %>%
  filter(grepl("ABATEDOURO|MATADOURO", TYPE))
lh_missing_list <- split(lh_missing, seq(nrow(lh_missing)))
for(i in 1:nrow(lh_missing)){
  lh_missing_list[[i]] <- bind_cols(lh_missing_list[[i]], munis_df) %>%
    select(-ROW_ID)
}
lh_missing_df <- bind_rows(lh_missing_list) %>%
  left_join(ppm_2022, by = "GEOCODE", relationship = "many-to-one") %>%
  left_join(urban, by = c("LH_GEOCODE" = "GEOCODE"), relationship = "many-to-one") %>%
  rename(LH_CLASSIFICATION = MUNI_CLASSIFICATION) %>%
  left_join(urban, by = c("GEOCODE" = "GEOCODE"), relationship = "many-to-one") %>%
  rename(GEOCODE_CLASSIFICATION = MUNI_CLASSIFICATION) %>%
  left_join(sigsif_summary, by = c("STATE" = "STATE_SLAUGHTER", "GEOCODE")) %>%
  mutate(NUM_HEAD = replace_na(NUM_HEAD, 0), 
         SIGSIF_PROP_FLOWS = replace_na(SIGSIF_PROP_FLOWS, 0)) %>%
  left_join(dist_matrix, by = c("LH_GEOCODE" = "DESTINATION", "GEOCODE" = "ORIGIN")) %>%
  left_join(neighbour_all_df, by = c("LH_GEOCODE" = "FOCAL_GEOCODE", "GEOCODE" = "NEIGHBOUR_GEOCODE")) %>%
  mutate(NEIGHBOUR = ifelse(is.na(NEIGHBOUR), "NOT NEIGHBOUR", NEIGHBOUR)) %>%
  mutate(SAME_STATE = ifelse(str_sub(LH_GEOCODE, start = 1, end = 2) == str_sub(GEOCODE, start = 1, end = 2), TRUE, FALSE)) %>%
  drop_na(LH_CLASSIFICATION) %>%
  drop_na(GEOCODE_CLASSIFICATION) %>%
  drop_na(SAME_STATE) %>%
  drop_na(DISTANCE_KM) %>%
  drop_na(GEOCODE)
  

# Add in the distance to the nearest SIF/SIE slaughterhouse (which is no the slaughterhouse-of-interest)
# NB a small number of duplicate rows are introduced, but this won't affect the modelling much
chk <- nrow(lh_missing_df)
lh_missing_df <- inner_join(lh_missing_df,
                 sif_distances,
                 by = c("GEOCODE" = "ORIGIN"),
                 relationship = "many-to-many") %>%
  filter(CNPJ8 != CNPJ8_SIF) %>%
  group_by(CNPJ8, LH_GEOCODE, GEOCODE, INSPECTION_LEVEL, TYPE) %>%
  filter(DISTANCE_KM_TO_NEXT_NEAREST_SIF == min(DISTANCE_KM_TO_NEXT_NEAREST_SIF)) %>%
  slice(1) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(-CNPJ8_SIF) %>%
  inner_join(sie_distances,
             by = c("GEOCODE" = "ORIGIN"),
             relationship = "many-to-many") %>%
  filter(CNPJ8 != CNPJ8_SIE) %>%
  group_by(CNPJ8, LH_GEOCODE, GEOCODE, INSPECTION_LEVEL, TYPE) %>%
  filter(DISTANCE_KM_TO_NEXT_NEAREST_SIE == min(DISTANCE_KM_TO_NEXT_NEAREST_SIE)) %>%
  slice(1) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(-CNPJ8_SIE) %>%
  distinct()


# Check there are no NAs in the data set
# map_lgl(df, ~ any(is.na(.x)))
stopifnot(sum(is.na(lh_missing_df)) == 0)

# Compare the actual and predicted PROP_FLOWS

# ... I include a correction, were we re-base the PROP_FLOWS to sum to 1 (i.e. a true-proportion)
lh_missing_df <- bind_cols(lh_missing_df, tibble("PRED_PROP_FLOWS" = ss_predictions$predictions))

proportion_summary <- lh_missing_df %>%

proportion_summary %>%

     subtitle = glue("Should sum to one in each case.

Then we rebase the proportions (per slaughterhouse) to sum to one.

Note: I drop municipalities with predicted volumes < 0.01% of flows, in order to reduce the size of the data.

# Rebase the predictions so they sum to 1 (per slaughterhouse)
lh_missing_df <- lh_missing_df %>%
  filter(PRED_PROP_FLOWS > 0.0001) %>%
  group_by(CNPJ8, LH_GEOCODE) %>%
  mutate(TOTAL_PRED_PROP_FLOWS = sum(PRED_PROP_FLOWS),
         PRED_PROP_FLOWS_CORRECTED = PRED_PROP_FLOWS / unique(TOTAL_PRED_PROP_FLOWS)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(CNPJ8, LH_GEOCODE, GEOCODE, PRED_PROP_FLOWS_CORRECTED) %>%
  filter(PRED_PROP_FLOWS_CORRECTED > 0) %>%
  group_by(CNPJ8, LH_GEOCODE) %>%
  nest(SUPPLY_SHED = c(GEOCODE, PRED_PROP_FLOWS_CORRECTED)) %>%
  ungroup()

Visualise predicted supply sheds

fn_plot_predicted_supply_sheds <- function(CNPJ8, LH_GEOCODE, SUPPLY_SHED, muni_centroids, states, scale_max) {
  munis_to_plot <-
    inner_join(munis, SUPPLY_SHED, by = c("GEOCODE" = "GEOCODE")) %>%
    mutate(TWO_DIGIT_CODE = str_sub(GEOCODE, start = 1, end = 2)) %>%
    left_join(state_dic, by = "TWO_DIGIT_CODE")
  location <-
    muni_centroids %>%
    filter(GEOCODE == LH_GEOCODE) %>%
    mutate(
      x = map_dbl(geometry, 1),
      y = map_dbl(geometry, 2), 
      TWO_DIGIT_CODE = str_sub(GEOCODE, start = 1, end = 2)
    ) %>%
    left_join(state_dic, by = "TWO_DIGIT_CODE")
  p <- ggplot() +
    geom_sf(data = states %>% filter(NM_ESTADO %in% unique(munis_to_plot$STATE_NAME)), fill = trase_country_background, col = trase_map_border) +
    geom_sf(data = munis_to_plot, aes(fill = PRED_PROP_FLOWS_CORRECTED * 100), col = NA) +
    geom_point(data = location, aes(x = x, y = y), col = "green") +
    scale_fill_gradient(
    name = bquote('% SOURCING'),
    low = trase_palettes$MapsNegative[[1]],
    high = trase_palettes$MapsNegative[[9]], 
    limits = c(0, 100)
  ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    coord_sf(datum = NA) +
    labs(
      title = paste0("Predicted sourcing of CNPJ8 ", CNPJ8, " in ", location$NAME, ", ", location$STATE_ABBR)
    ) +
    theme(axis.title = element_blank())
  return(p)
}
pmap(
  .l = lh_missing_df %>% sample_n(size = 4),
  .f = fn_plot_predicted_supply_sheds,
  muni_centroids = muni_centroids,
  states = states
)
